04217nam a22006135i 9780226547855DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265478557 a10.7208/97802265478552doi  a(DE-B1597)521374  a(OCoLC)1035556605  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGN476.73b.V64 2019 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a581.6342231 aVoeks, Robert A., eauthor.14aThe Ethnobotany of Eden :bRethinking the Jungle Medicine Narrative /cRobert A. Voeks. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b49 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter One. God's Medicine Chest -- tChapter Two. Terra Mythica -- tChapter Three. People in the Forest -- tChapter Four. Green Gold -- tChapter Five. Weeds in the Garden -- tChapter Six. Gender and Healing -- tChapter eight. Forgetting the Forest -- tChapter nine. Environmental Narratives -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the mysterious and pristine forests of the tropics, a wealth of ethnobotanical panaceas and shamanic knowledge promises cures for everything from cancer and AIDS to the common cold. To access such miracles, we need only to discover and protect these medicinal treasures before they succumb to the corrosive forces of the modern world. A compelling biocultural story, certainly, and a popular perspective on the lands and peoples of equatorial latitudes-but true? Only in part. In The Ethnobotany of Eden, geographer Robert A. Voeks unravels the long lianas of history and occasional strands of truth that gave rise to this irresistible jungle medicine narrative. By exploring the interconnected worlds of anthropology, botany, and geography, Voeks shows that well-intentioned scientists and environmentalists originally crafted the jungle narrative with the primary goal of saving the world's tropical rainforests from destruction. It was a strategy deployed to address a pressing environmental problem, one that appeared at a propitious point in history just as the Western world was taking a more globalized view of environmental issues. And yet, although supported by science and its practitioners, the story was also underpinned by a persuasive mix of myth, sentimentality, and nostalgia for a long-lost tropical Eden. Resurrecting the fascinating history of plant prospecting in the tropics, from the colonial era to the present day, The Ethnobotany of Eden rewrites with modern science the degradation narrative we've built up around tropical forests, revealing the entangled origins of our fables of forest cures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEthnobotanyzTropics. 0aTraditional medicinezTropics. 4aAfrican diaspora. 4aTorrid Zone. 4acolonial period. 4acultural erosion. 4aenvironmental narrative. 4aethnobotany. 4agender. 4amedicinal plants. 4atropical rainforest. 4aweeds. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226547855423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226547855.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles